-- PART 4: diversity-of-life (48 easy, 48 medium, 49 hard)

('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What are the three domains of life?', 'Bacteria, Viruses, Eukarya', 'Bacteria, Archaea, Eukarya', 'Prokaryotes, Eukaryotes, Viruses', 'Plants, Animals, Fungi', 'B', 'The three-domain system (Woese and Fox) classifies all cellular life into Bacteria, Archaea, and Eukarya based primarily on ribosomal RNA sequence comparisons.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the main difference between prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells?', 'Prokaryotes have mitochondria; eukaryotes do not', 'Eukaryotes have a membrane-bound nucleus; prokaryotes do not', 'Prokaryotes are always larger than eukaryotes', 'Eukaryotes lack a cell wall', 'B', 'The defining characteristic of eukaryotes is a membrane-enclosed nucleus containing their DNA; prokaryotes (Bacteria and Archaea) lack a membrane-bound nucleus, and their DNA is in the cytoplasm (nucleoid region).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'Which kingdom includes multicellular organisms that obtain nutrients by absorbing organic matter from their environment?', 'Animalia', 'Plantae', 'Fungi', 'Protista', 'C', 'Fungi are heterotrophic decomposers that secrete digestive enzymes externally and absorb the resulting small molecules; they are the principal decomposers in most ecosystems.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the binomial nomenclature system?', 'A system using numbers to classify organisms by kingdom', 'A two-part scientific naming system using genus and species names', 'A system classifying organisms by their physical traits only', 'A method of DNA barcoding', 'B', 'Linnaean binomial nomenclature gives each species a two-part Latin name: the first part (capitalized) is the genus and the second part (lowercase) is the species epithet (e.g., Homo sapiens).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the correct order of taxonomic ranks from broadest to most specific?', 'Species, Genus, Family, Order, Class, Phylum, Kingdom, Domain', 'Domain, Kingdom, Phylum, Class, Order, Family, Genus, Species', 'Kingdom, Phylum, Class, Order, Family, Species, Genus, Domain', 'Domain, Phylum, Kingdom, Class, Family, Order, Genus, Species', 'B', 'The standard taxonomic hierarchy from broadest to most specific is: Domain → Kingdom → Phylum → Class → Order → Family → Genus → Species.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What are viruses?', 'Single-celled organisms classified in the domain Bacteria', 'Non-cellular particles with genetic material surrounded by a protein coat, requiring a host cell to replicate', 'Fungi-like organisms that cause disease in plants', 'Small prokaryotes without a cell wall', 'B', 'Viruses are acellular entities consisting of nucleic acid (DNA or RNA) enclosed in a protein capsid (sometimes enveloped by a lipid membrane); they are not alive in the traditional sense and can only replicate inside a host cell.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'Which of the following is a characteristic unique to plants?', 'Having a cell wall', 'Performing photosynthesis using chlorophyll b', 'Having mitochondria', 'Being multicellular', 'B', 'Plants uniquely contain chlorophyll b (in addition to chlorophyll a) as an accessory photosynthetic pigment. While other features like cell walls (also in fungi and bacteria) and multicellularity are shared with other groups.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is an endosymbiont?', 'A parasite that destroys host cells', 'An organism living inside another organism in a mutually beneficial relationship', 'A bacterium that lives on the surface of plants', 'A virus that integrates into the host genome', 'B', 'An endosymbiont lives inside a host cell in a symbiotic relationship; the endosymbiotic theory proposes that mitochondria and chloroplasts evolved from endosymbiotic bacteria taken up by ancestral eukaryotic cells.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the main evidence for the endosymbiotic theory?', 'Mitochondria and chloroplasts lack DNA', 'Mitochondria and chloroplasts have their own circular DNA, double membranes, and ribosomes similar to those of bacteria', 'Mitochondria can survive outside the cell', 'Chloroplasts are formed from the nucleus', 'B', 'Supporting evidence for endosymbiosis: organelles have their own circular (bacterial-type) DNA, possess prokaryotic-sized ribosomes sensitive to bacterial antibiotics (not eukaryotic), have double membranes (inner = original bacterial membrane), and reproduce by binary fission.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is a phylogenetic tree?', 'A diagram showing the food web of an ecosystem', 'A branching diagram showing evolutionary relationships among organisms', 'A family tree showing an organism''s individual ancestors', 'A map of gene locations on a chromosome', 'B', 'A phylogenetic tree (cladogram) represents the evolutionary history and relationships among taxa, with branch points (nodes) representing common ancestors and branch lengths sometimes representing evolutionary distance.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What type of reproduction produces offspring genetically identical to the parent?', 'Sexual reproduction', 'Asexual reproduction', 'Conjugation', 'Meiosis', 'B', 'Asexual reproduction (binary fission, budding, vegetative propagation, etc.) produces genetically identical offspring (clones) because it does not involve the mixing of genetic material from two parents.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the cell wall of bacteria primarily made of?', 'Cellulose', 'Chitin', 'Peptidoglycan', 'Phospholipids', 'C', 'Bacterial cell walls are composed of peptidoglycan (murein), a polymer of sugars (NAM and NAG) cross-linked by short peptide chains; this rigid structure gives bacteria shape and protects against osmotic lysis.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is a clade?', 'A group of organisms sharing only physical appearance', 'A group consisting of an ancestor and all of its descendants', 'A group of unrelated species living in the same habitat', 'A type of chemical used to classify organisms', 'B', 'A clade (or monophyletic group) includes a common ancestor and ALL of its descendants — it represents a complete branch of the tree of life. Clades are the fundamental units of cladistic classification.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'Which structure allows some bacteria to attach to surfaces and form biofilms?', 'Plasmids', 'Pili (fimbriae)', 'Ribosomes', 'Nucleoid', 'B', 'Pili are hair-like proteinaceous appendages on bacterial surfaces; fimbriae (short pili) help bacteria attach to host tissues and surfaces, and type IV pili enable motility and are involved in biofilm formation and conjugation.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is a prion?', 'A type of virus without nucleic acid', 'An infectious misfolded protein that causes other proteins to misfold, leading to neurodegenerative disease', 'A small circular RNA molecule', 'A bacterial endospore', 'B', 'Prions are infectious agents composed entirely of misfolded proteins (PrPSc) that cause normal cellular prion protein (PrPC) to adopt an abnormal conformation; they cause fatal neurodegenerative diseases such as BSE (mad cow disease) and Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease in humans.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the difference between gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria?', 'Gram-negative bacteria have no cell wall', 'Gram-positive bacteria have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall that retains crystal violet stain; gram-negative bacteria have a thin peptidoglycan layer and an outer lipopolysaccharide membrane', 'Gram-positive bacteria are always pathogenic', 'Gram-negative bacteria stain purple with crystal violet', 'B', 'Gram staining differentiates bacteria by cell wall structure: gram-positive bacteria retain the crystal violet-iodine complex (stain purple) due to their thick peptidoglycan layer; gram-negative bacteria are decolorized and take up the red safranin counterstain, due to their thin peptidoglycan and outer membrane.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is a eukaryote?', 'Any organism without a cell membrane', 'An organism whose cells contain a membrane-bound nucleus and other membrane-bound organelles', 'An organism with no DNA', 'A single-celled organism without organelles', 'B', 'Eukaryotes (animals, plants, fungi, protists) have cells with a true membrane-bound nucleus and numerous organelles (mitochondria, ER, Golgi, etc.); this complexity distinguishes them from prokaryotes.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is an autotroph?', 'An organism that obtains nutrients by eating other organisms', 'An organism that produces its own organic food from inorganic compounds using light or chemical energy', 'An organism that gets nutrients through absorption', 'An organism that requires oxygen to survive', 'B', 'Autotrophs (producers) synthesize organic molecules from inorganic sources: photoautotrophs use light energy (plants, algae, cyanobacteria) and chemoautotrophs use chemical energy (deep-sea hydrothermal vent bacteria).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is convergent evolution?', 'The evolution of the same trait in two species from a common ancestor', 'The independent evolution of similar traits in unrelated lineages due to similar selective pressures', 'When two species evolve together influencing each other', 'The loss of traits due to relaxed selection', 'B', 'Convergent evolution occurs when unrelated species independently evolve similar adaptations in response to similar environments or lifestyles (e.g., wings in birds and bats, or streamlined body shape in dolphins and fish).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the significance of bilateral symmetry in animals?', 'It allows all body parts to regenerate if damaged', 'It is associated with cephalization, directional movement, and distinct dorsal/ventral and anterior/posterior body axes', 'Bilateral symmetry is found in all animals', 'It restricts animals to living in flat environments', 'B', 'Bilateral symmetry (mirror-image left and right sides) is associated with cephalization (concentration of sensory organs at the anterior end), directional locomotion, and the development of a complex nervous system — adaptive advantages for active, directional predators.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What are the primary characteristics of the animal kingdom?', 'Animals are autotrophic, multicellular, and have cell walls', 'Animals are multicellular, heterotrophic, lack cell walls, and most can move at some point in their life cycle', 'Animals are unicellular and heterotrophic', 'Animals are photosynthetic and sessile', 'B', 'Animals (kingdom Animalia) are multicellular eukaryotes that are heterotrophic (obtain nutrients by ingestion), lack cell walls, and typically have the ability to move during at least some stage of their life cycle.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the role of decomposers in ecosystems?', 'They produce organic matter from inorganic molecules', 'They break down dead organic matter into inorganic nutrients, recycling elements through the ecosystem', 'They consume plants and transfer energy to carnivores', 'They protect other organisms from pathogens', 'B', 'Decomposers (mainly bacteria and fungi) break down dead organic matter (detritus) into inorganic nutrients (CO₂, nitrate, phosphate), recycling essential elements back to the abiotic environment for use by producers.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What distinguishes a viroid from a virus?', 'Viroids are made of protein while viruses are made of RNA', 'Viroids are infectious RNA molecules with no protein coat that infect plants', 'Viroids are large DNA viruses that infect bacteria', 'Viroids and viruses are identical in structure', 'B', 'Viroids are the smallest known infectious agents — small, circular, single-stranded RNA molecules with no protein coat. They infect only plants (e.g., causing potato spindle tuber disease) and likely disrupt plant regulatory processes.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is horizontal gene transfer (HGT)?', 'The transfer of genes from parent to offspring during reproduction', 'The transfer of genetic material between organisms of the same or different species other than by reproduction', 'The transfer of genes from the nucleus to organelles', 'Genes moving from one chromosome to another within the same cell', 'B', 'HGT (also called lateral gene transfer) is the transfer of genetic material between cells other than parent-to-offspring; it is common in bacteria (via transformation, conjugation, transduction) and is a major driver of antibiotic resistance spread.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is a plasmid?', 'The main bacterial chromosome', 'A small, circular, extrachromosomal DNA molecule that replicates independently in bacteria', 'A type of RNA used in translation', 'A protein used to repair bacterial cell walls', 'B', 'Plasmids are small, circular double-stranded DNA molecules found in bacteria (and some eukaryotes) that replicate independently of the chromosomal DNA and often carry genes conferring advantages such as antibiotic resistance.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'Which of the following is an example of a protist?', 'Streptococcus bacteria', 'Penicillium mold', 'Paramecium', 'Moss plant', 'C', 'Paramecium is a ciliate protist — a unicellular eukaryote with complex organelles. Protists are a diverse, polyphyletic group of eukaryotes that do not fit neatly into the plant, animal, or fungi kingdoms.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the difference between a primary and secondary consumer?', 'Primary consumers eat decomposers; secondary consumers eat plants', 'Primary consumers eat producers (plants); secondary consumers eat primary consumers', 'Both are identical except that secondary consumers are larger', 'Primary consumers are animals; secondary consumers are plants', 'B', 'Primary consumers (herbivores) eat producers (autotrophs); secondary consumers (carnivores/omnivores) eat primary consumers, placing them at a higher trophic level in the food chain.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is coevolution?', 'The evolution of two populations within the same species', 'Reciprocal evolutionary change in interacting species, where each species acts as a selective agent on the other', 'The simultaneous extinction of two species', 'Evolution driven only by climate change', 'B', 'Coevolution occurs when two interacting species exert reciprocal selective pressure on each other over evolutionary time (e.g., predator-prey arms races, flower-pollinator specialization, host-parasite relationships).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the function of spores in fungi and plants?', 'Spores are the primary nutrient-storage structures', 'Spores are reproductive units that can develop into new individuals, often resistant to harsh environmental conditions', 'Spores are the main photosynthetic structures in plants', 'Spores produce sex hormones for reproduction', 'B', 'Spores are haploid reproductive units produced by meiosis (in diploid organisms) or mitosis; they are dispersed (by wind, water, animals) and germinate under favorable conditions to produce new organisms — a key dispersal and survival mechanism.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'Which invertebrate phylum contains organisms with segmented bodies, jointed appendages, and an exoskeleton?', 'Mollusca', 'Annelida', 'Arthropoda', 'Echinodermata', 'C', 'Arthropoda (insects, arachnids, crustaceans, myriapods) is characterized by a segmented body, jointed appendages (allowing precise movement), and a hard exoskeleton of chitin — the most species-rich animal phylum.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the main characteristic of chordates?', 'Having a four-chambered heart', 'At some point in their development, possessing a notochord, dorsal hollow nerve cord, pharyngeal slits, and post-anal tail', 'Having a mineralized skeleton', 'Being exclusively vertebrates', 'B', 'All chordates (at some developmental stage) share four features: a notochord (flexible support rod), a dorsal hollow nerve cord (becomes the brain/spinal cord in vertebrates), pharyngeal slits (gill slits in fish, modified in tetrapods), and a muscular post-anal tail.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is an extremophile?', 'A plant that grows in extreme climates', 'An organism that thrives in extreme environmental conditions (high temperature, salt, acidity, etc.)', 'An animal adapted to migrate long distances', 'A parasitic organism that lives inside extreme hosts', 'B', 'Extremophiles are organisms (mostly Archaea, but also some Bacteria and eukaryotes) that thrive under extreme conditions hostile to most life: thermophiles (high temperature), halophiles (high salt), acidophiles (low pH), piezophiles (high pressure), etc.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is genetic drift?', 'Changes in allele frequency due to natural selection', 'Random changes in allele frequencies in a population due to chance events, especially significant in small populations', 'The transfer of genes between species via horizontal gene transfer', 'The directional evolution of a population toward a fitness peak', 'B', 'Genetic drift is the random change in allele frequencies due to chance sampling events in finite populations; its effects are most pronounced in small populations where it can cause fixation or loss of alleles regardless of their adaptive value.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is a keystone species?', 'The most abundant species in an ecosystem', 'A species with a disproportionately large impact on community structure relative to its abundance', 'The first species to colonize a new habitat', 'A species that produces oxygen for the ecosystem', 'B', 'A keystone species has a disproportionately large effect on its ecosystem relative to its biomass; its removal causes dramatic changes in community structure (e.g., sea otters maintaining kelp forest ecosystems by preying on sea urchins).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'Which type of symbiosis benefits one organism while harming the other?', 'Mutualism', 'Commensalism', 'Parasitism', 'Competition', 'C', 'Parasitism is a symbiotic relationship in which one organism (the parasite) benefits by exploiting or harming the other (the host), while the host suffers reduced fitness.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What distinguishes vascular plants from non-vascular plants?', 'Vascular plants are always aquatic', 'Vascular plants have specialized conducting tissue (xylem and phloem) for transporting water and nutrients', 'Non-vascular plants reproduce by seeds', 'Vascular plants cannot perform photosynthesis', 'B', 'Vascular plants (tracheophytes) have xylem (transporting water and minerals) and phloem (transporting sugars and other organic molecules) — allowing them to grow tall and colonize terrestrial habitats. Non-vascular plants (bryophytes like mosses) lack these tissues and are restricted to moist environments.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is an ecological niche?', 'The physical habitat of a species', 'The full range of biotic and abiotic conditions an organism can tolerate, along with its functional role in the ecosystem', 'The geographic range of a species', 'The food an organism eats', 'B', 'The ecological niche is the multidimensional space of all conditions and resources a species can use (fundamental niche), modified by competitors and predators to the realized niche — it encompasses habitat use, diet, activity patterns, and the species'' functional role.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is an invasive species?', 'A native species that is very abundant', 'A non-native species introduced to a new area where it proliferates and negatively impacts the native ecosystem', 'A species that lives only in protected reserves', 'A species threatened with extinction in its native range', 'B', 'An invasive species is a non-indigenous organism that, when introduced to a new environment, spreads rapidly (often lacking natural predators or competitors) and causes ecological or economic harm (e.g., zebra mussels, kudzu, cane toads).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the role of mycorrhizal fungi in plant communities?', 'They parasitize plant roots and reduce nutrient uptake', 'They form mutualistic associations with plant roots, extending the root system and dramatically improving water and mineral (especially phosphate) uptake in exchange for carbohydrates', 'They decompose plant leaf litter only', 'They compete with plants for water in the soil', 'B', 'Mycorrhizal fungi form intimate associations with most plant roots; fungal hyphae extend far into the soil, increasing the effective absorptive surface area for water and nutrients (especially phosphate and nitrogen), while the plant supplies the fungus with photosynthetically derived sugars.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is natural selection?', 'Random changes in allele frequencies due to chance', 'The differential survival and reproduction of individuals with heritable traits better suited to their environment', 'The tendency for populations to inbreed', 'The migration of individuals between populations', 'B', 'Natural selection is the mechanism by which heritable traits that increase an organism''s fitness (survival and reproductive success) in a given environment become more common in subsequent generations — the key mechanism of adaptive evolution.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is ecological succession?', 'The immediate recovery of an ecosystem after a disturbance', 'The gradual, directional change in the species composition of a community over time, from a pioneer community to a climax community', 'The seasonal variation in species abundance', 'The spread of invasive species through a habitat', 'B', 'Ecological succession is the predictable sequence of community changes over time: primary succession begins on bare substrate (pioneer species → intermediate stages → climax community); secondary succession occurs after a disturbance removes the community but leaves the soil intact.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the difference between homologous and analogous structures?', 'Homologous structures have the same function; analogous structures have the same origin', 'Homologous structures share a common evolutionary origin (may have different functions); analogous structures share a similar function but evolved independently in unrelated lineages', 'They are identical in both origin and function', 'Analogous structures are found only in closely related species', 'B', 'Homologous structures (e.g., the forelimbs of mammals) share common ancestry and underlying structure despite possibly different functions — evidence of descent with modification. Analogous structures (e.g., bird wing and butterfly wing) have similar functions but evolved independently (convergent evolution), not from a common ancestor.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the definition of a biological species?', 'A group of organisms with identical DNA', 'A group of populations whose members have the potential to interbreed and produce fertile offspring, isolated from other groups by reproductive barriers', 'All organisms living in the same geographic area', 'A group of organisms that look identical', 'B', 'The biological species concept (Mayr) defines a species as a group of actually or potentially interbreeding natural populations that are reproductively isolated from other such groups — reproductive isolation is the key criterion.'),

-- medium diversity-of-life
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What evidence do molecular data provide about the relationship between Archaea and Eukarya?', 'Archaea and Bacteria are more closely related to each other than either is to Eukarya', 'Archaea are more closely related to Eukarya than to Bacteria; many archaeal information-processing genes (transcription, translation, DNA replication) are homologous to eukaryotic genes, while Bacteria are the outgroup', 'All three domains are equally related to each other', 'Eukarya evolved from Bacteria, not Archaea', 'B', 'Ribosomal RNA phylogenies and genome-wide analyses consistently group Archaea and Eukarya as sister taxa. Archaea share many core features with eukaryotes: similar RNA polymerases, histone-like proteins, DNA replication machinery, and intron-containing genes — suggesting Eukarya evolved from within Archaea (the Asgard hypothesis).'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the Hardy-Weinberg principle, and what conditions must be met for a population to be in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium?', 'Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium means natural selection is maximized in a population', 'If allele frequencies p and q satisfy p + q = 1, genotype frequencies will be p², 2pq, and q² if: no mutation, no gene flow, random mating, large population (no drift), and no selection occur', 'Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium requires strong directional selection', 'The principle applies only to haploid organisms', 'B', 'The Hardy-Weinberg principle states that allele and genotype frequencies remain constant across generations in an ideal population (no evolution occurring) if five conditions are met: no mutation, no gene flow, random mating, very large population size (minimizing drift), and no natural selection. Deviations from expected frequencies indicate evolutionary forces acting on the population.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'How does the lytic cycle of a bacteriophage differ from the lysogenic cycle?', 'The lytic cycle integrates viral DNA into the host chromosome; the lysogenic cycle does not', 'In the lytic cycle, the phage replicates immediately, produces new phages, and lyses the host cell; in the lysogenic cycle, the phage DNA integrates as a prophage and replicates passively with the host, remaining dormant until induced', 'The lysogenic cycle always kills the host cell faster than the lytic cycle', 'Only the lytic cycle can be transmitted horizontally', 'B', 'Lytic: phage injects DNA → hijacks host machinery → replicates → lyses host → releases progeny phages. Lysogenic: phage DNA integrates into host chromosome as prophage → replicates with host through divisions → under stress (UV, etc.), the prophage is excised and enters the lytic cycle.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is allopatric speciation and how does it differ from sympatric speciation?', 'Allopatric speciation occurs in the same geographic area; sympatric speciation requires physical separation', 'Allopatric speciation occurs when populations are geographically isolated, allowing divergence into separate species; sympatric speciation occurs in the same geographic area through reproductive isolation by other means (polyploidy, ecological specialization)', 'Both processes require the same conditions but differ only in timescale', 'Sympatric speciation always involves polyploidy; allopatric never does', 'B', 'Allopatric speciation: physical barriers (mountains, water bodies) separate populations → genetic divergence through mutation, drift, selection → reproductive isolation evolves → species. Sympatric speciation: without geographic isolation, reproductive isolation arises via polyploidy (common in plants), disruptive selection, or ecological specialization within the same area.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the significance of the Cambrian explosion in the history of animal life?', 'The Cambrian explosion was when the first photosynthetic organisms appeared', 'The Cambrian explosion (~541 million years ago) saw the rapid appearance in the fossil record of most major animal body plans within a geologically short time, representing an extraordinary diversification of multicellular animal life', 'The Cambrian explosion was caused by the first mass extinction event', 'The Cambrian explosion marks when the first vertebrates appeared on land', 'B', 'The Cambrian explosion (~541–520 Ma) produced most extant animal phyla within ~20 million years — a dramatic diversification hypothesized to have been driven by increasing O₂ levels, the evolution of eyes and predation, ecological opportunity, and possibly key genetic innovations (Hox genes).'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'How do R-selected and K-selected species differ in their life history strategies?', 'R-selected species have long lifespans and few offspring; K-selected species produce many offspring', 'R-selected species produce many small offspring with little parental care and high mortality rates; K-selected species produce few large offspring with extensive parental care in stable environments near carrying capacity', 'R-selected species are found only in tropical environments', 'Both strategies produce equal numbers of offspring but differ in parental care', 'B', 'r-selection favors rapid reproduction, many small offspring, early maturity, and little parental investment — suited to unstable, resource-rich environments (weeds, insects). K-selection favors slow reproduction, few large offspring, late maturity, and heavy parental investment — suited to stable, resource-limited environments near carrying capacity (elephants, humans, albatrosses).'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the molecular clock hypothesis, and what are its assumptions and limitations?', 'The molecular clock states that all genes mutate at the same rate regardless of function', 'The molecular clock proposes that DNA sequences accumulate mutations at an approximately constant rate over time, allowing estimation of divergence dates; it assumes roughly neutral mutations in non-functional regions and can be calibrated by fossil records but is affected by differences in generation time and selection pressure', 'The molecular clock is based on morphological change rates', 'The molecular clock applies only to mitochondrial DNA, not nuclear genes', 'B', 'The molecular clock uses mutation rates in homologous sequences to estimate when taxa diverged. Assumptions: approximately constant mutation rates, neutral evolution. Limitations: rates vary among lineages (generation time effects, metabolic rate, selection), so relaxed molecular clocks that allow rate variation among branches have replaced strict clocks; calibration with fossil dates is essential.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What distinguishes a monophyletic group from paraphyletic and polyphyletic groups?', 'Monophyletic groups include only some of an ancestor''s descendants', 'A monophyletic (clade) includes an ancestor and ALL its descendants; paraphyletic excludes some descendants; polyphyletic lacks the common ancestor entirely', 'Paraphyletic groups are the most evolutionarily meaningful', 'Polyphyletic groups share a common ancestor not shared by others', 'B', 'Monophyletic (clade): common ancestor + all descendants — the only natural, evolutionarily meaningful group used in modern classification. Paraphyletic: common ancestor + some descendants (e.g., "reptiles" excluding birds). Polyphyletic: members share convergent traits but not a common ancestor shared exclusively by them (e.g., "warm-blooded animals" grouping birds + mammals).'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'How do mycorrhizal networks function ecologically beyond individual plant-fungal pairs?', 'Mycorrhizal networks are relevant only for individual plant nutrition', 'Mycorrhizal networks (wood wide web) connect multiple plants in a community; carbon, water, and nutrients (especially phosphate and nitrogen) can be transferred between plants through fungal hyphae, potentially supporting seedlings in shade and linking plant community responses', 'Mycorrhizal networks only allow fungi to extract nutrients from plants without any return benefit', 'The networks transfer oxygen between plant root systems', 'B', 'The common mycorrhizal network links root systems of different plant individuals and species; carbon isotope tracer experiments show net carbon transfer from larger, photosynthetically active plants to shaded seedlings. The network also facilitates redistribution of phosphorus, nitrogen, and potentially signaling molecules, raising questions about community-level resource sharing and plant communication.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is directional selection, and how does it differ from disruptive and stabilizing selection?', 'Directional selection maintains the mean phenotype unchanged', 'Directional selection shifts the mean phenotype toward one extreme; stabilizing selection favors the intermediate phenotype and reduces variance; disruptive selection favors both extremes over the intermediate, potentially driving divergence or speciation', 'Stabilizing selection always increases genetic diversity', 'Disruptive selection moves the population mean toward one extreme', 'B', 'Directional selection: one extreme phenotype has highest fitness (e.g., antibiotic resistance). Stabilizing selection: intermediate phenotype favored, reducing variation (e.g., human birth weight). Disruptive selection: both extremes have higher fitness than intermediate, increasing bimodal variation and potentially driving sympatric speciation.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'How does antibiotic resistance evolve in bacterial populations?', 'Bacteria intentionally mutate to resist antibiotics when exposed to them', 'Resistance alleles arise by random mutation; in the presence of antibiotics, resistant bacteria survive and reproduce while susceptible bacteria are killed — natural selection enriches the resistance allele in the population', 'Bacteria acquire resistance genes from human cells during infection', 'Antibiotic resistance is always encoded on the bacterial chromosome, never on plasmids', 'B', 'Antibiotic resistance evolution: (1) random mutations or horizontal gene transfer produce resistant variants before any antibiotic exposure; (2) antibiotic use kills susceptible individuals, removing their contribution to the next generation; (3) resistant individuals reproduce, increasing the frequency of resistance alleles — classic directional natural selection. Resistance is transmitted between strains via plasmid conjugation.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the role of the alternation of generations in the plant life cycle?', 'Alternation of generations refers to seasonal changes in plant appearance', 'Plant life cycles alternate between a multicellular diploid sporophyte (produces haploid spores by meiosis) and a multicellular haploid gametophyte (produces gametes by mitosis); the relative dominance shifts from gametophyte (mosses) to sporophyte (vascular plants)', 'Both the sporophyte and gametophyte are diploid in all plants', 'Alternation of generations is unique to animals', 'B', 'Alternation of generations in plants: the diploid sporophyte (2n) undergoes meiosis to produce haploid spores, which develop into the haploid gametophyte (n), which produces gametes by mitosis; fertilization restores the diploid sporophyte. The trend in plant evolution is toward reduced, dependent gametophytes and dominant sporophytes.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the bottleneck effect, and how does it differ from the founder effect?', 'Both effects increase genetic diversity by introducing new alleles', 'The bottleneck effect is a severe reduction in population size due to a catastrophic event, drastically reducing genetic diversity; the founder effect occurs when a small subgroup establishes a new population, also reducing diversity — both are forms of genetic drift', 'The bottleneck effect involves natural selection; the founder effect does not', 'The founder effect applies only to plant populations', 'B', 'Both are extreme examples of genetic drift: the bottleneck occurs when a disaster reduces population to a small fraction of its original size (survivors'' alleles may not represent original variation); the founder effect occurs when a few individuals colonize a new area, establishing a new population with low diversity reflecting the founders'' genotypes.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'How do angiosperms differ from gymnosperms in terms of reproductive structures?', 'Gymnosperms have flowers; angiosperms have cones', 'Angiosperms have flowers and enclosed seeds within fruits (derived from the ovary wall); gymnosperms have "naked" seeds borne on cone scales without an enclosing ovary', 'Both produce identical reproductive structures', 'Angiosperms produce seeds; gymnosperms produce only spores', 'B', 'Angiosperms (flowering plants) have ovules enclosed within an ovary, which develops into fruit containing seeds after fertilization; the double fertilization produces both the embryo (2n) and endosperm (3n). Gymnosperms (conifers, cycads, ginkgo, gnetophytes) produce seeds that develop exposed on cone scales, not enclosed in an ovary or fruit.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the competitive exclusion principle, and what allows two species to coexist despite competing for similar resources?', 'Two species always coexist because they never compete for exactly the same resources', 'The competitive exclusion principle states that two species competing for identical resources cannot coexist indefinitely — one will outcompete the other; coexistence is possible through niche differentiation (character displacement), temporal/spatial partitioning, or frequency-dependent selection', 'Competition always drives both species to extinction', 'The principle applies only to predator-prey relationships', 'B', 'Gause''s competitive exclusion principle: two species with identical niches cannot coexist because one will have even a slight competitive advantage. Coexistence is facilitated by niche differentiation (resource partitioning, habitat, time) reducing direct competition. Character displacement (divergence of resource use under competition) is an evolutionary response.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'How do CRISPR-Cas systems provide adaptive immunity in bacteria?', 'CRISPR destroys bacterial DNA when viral sequences are detected', 'Bacteria capture short sequences from invading phage DNA and insert them into CRISPR arrays; upon re-infection, CRISPR RNA (crRNA) guides Cas proteins to the matching phage DNA, which is cleaved — providing sequence-specific immunity', 'CRISPR only functions in eukaryotes to edit genes', 'CRISPR RNAs activate the bacterial immune complement system', 'B', 'Bacterial CRISPR-Cas adaptive immunity: (1) Adaptation — Cas1/Cas2 integrate a short protospacer from invading phage DNA between CRISPR repeats; (2) Expression — the CRISPR array is transcribed into pre-crRNA and processed into individual crRNAs; (3) Interference — the crRNA:Cas effector complex (e.g., Cas9) binds target phage DNA with a PAM sequence and cleaves both strands, destroying the phage.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'Why is the concept of punctuated equilibrium significant in evolutionary biology?', 'Punctuated equilibrium proposes that evolution does not occur', 'Punctuated equilibrium proposes that species remain relatively unchanged (stasis) for long periods and then undergo rapid evolutionary change (speciation) in geologically brief intervals, which better explains gaps in the fossil record than phyletic gradualism', 'Punctuated equilibrium explains why all evolution is driven by mass extinctions', 'Punctuated equilibrium suggests natural selection does not cause speciation', 'B', 'Eldredge and Gould''s punctuated equilibrium model proposes that most evolutionary change occurs during speciation events (concentrated in small, peripheral populations, leaving few fossils) and not gradually across the full range — explaining the observed pattern in the fossil record of long stasis interrupted by sudden appearance of new forms.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the difference between r and K selection in relation to population dynamics?', 'r and K selection are identical concepts with different names', 'r represents the intrinsic rate of population growth; K represents the carrying capacity; r-strategists have high r and low K, while K-strategists maximize fitness near K with low r and high investment per offspring', 'K-strategists are always found in unstable environments', 'r represents carrying capacity; K represents growth rate', 'B', 'In population dynamics, r is the intrinsic rate of natural increase and K is the carrying capacity. r-strategists (weedy species) maximize r: rapid growth, many offspring, short lifespan. K-strategists maximize fitness near carrying capacity: slow reproduction, few offspring, high parental investment, longer lifespan. These represent endpoints of a life history continuum.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is a mutualism, and provide an example involving an animal?', 'A mutualism harms one organism and benefits another', 'Mutualism is a symbiotic relationship that benefits both interacting species; an example is the relationship between cleaner fish (wrasse) and larger fish, where the cleaner removes parasites (gaining food) and the host gains parasite removal (improved health)', 'A mutualism is a parasitic relationship where the parasite benefits', 'Mutualism occurs only between plants and fungi', 'B', 'Mutualism benefits both partners. Animal mutualisms include: clownfish and sea anemones (fish gains protection; anemone gains cleaning/defense), oxpeckers and large herbivores (bird gets food; herbivore gets parasite removal), and gut microbiome relationships (bacteria digest food for humans; bacteria get nutrients and habitat).'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is gene flow and how does it affect speciation?', 'Gene flow increases genetic differentiation between populations, promoting speciation', 'Gene flow (migration of individuals or gametes between populations) introduces new alleles and homogenizes allele frequencies between populations, reducing genetic differentiation and acting against speciation', 'Gene flow and genetic drift are the same process', 'Gene flow is irrelevant to population genetics', 'B', 'Gene flow (migration of individuals carrying genes between populations) introduces new alleles (increasing diversity within a recipient population) and equalizes allele frequencies between populations, counteracting the divergence needed for speciation. High gene flow maintains populations as a single evolutionary unit; reduced gene flow allows divergence that can lead to speciation.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'How does the plant hormone ethylene regulate fruit ripening, and what is its molecular basis?', 'Ethylene blocks ripening by inhibiting enzyme production', 'Ethylene is a gaseous hormone that binds ER-localized receptors (ETR1), inactivating CTR1 and activating EIN2/EIN3 transcription factors, which upregulate genes encoding cell wall-softening enzymes (polygalacturonase, cellulase), pigment conversion enzymes, and sugar metabolizing enzymes that coordinate ripening', 'Ethylene is a plant hormone that promotes seed germination but not fruit ripening', 'Ethylene is produced only in the roots and transported to fruit', 'B', 'Ethylene (CH₂=CH₂) is produced by ACC synthase and ACC oxidase from methionine, and is released as a gas from ripening fruit. It binds the ETR1 receptor family → relieves CTR1 kinase repression of EIN2 → EIN2 C-terminus activates EIN3/EIL1 transcription factors → transcription of ripening genes (polygalacturonase, lycopene synthase, amylase) — a positive feedback autocatalytic ripening response.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is kin selection, and how does it explain the evolution of altruistic behavior?', 'Kin selection explains why animals with many relatives avoid competition', 'Kin selection predicts that altruistic behavior toward genetic relatives evolves when the inclusive fitness benefit (to relatives, weighted by relatedness) exceeds the direct fitness cost to the actor — formalized as Hamilton''s rule: rB > C', 'Kin selection applies only to insects', 'Kin selection requires animals to consciously identify relatives', 'B', 'Hamilton''s rule (rB > C): altruism evolves when the benefit B to the recipient, weighted by genetic relatedness r, exceeds the cost C to the actor. For siblings (r = 0.5), helping 3 siblings survive reproductively is worth 1 offspring of your own. This explains worker bees (r = 0.75 to sisters in haplodiploid system), ground squirrel alarm calls, and other seemingly selfless behaviors.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the difference between primary and secondary succession in ecological communities?', 'Primary succession starts on previously vegetated land; secondary succession starts on bare rock', 'Primary succession begins on a substrate with no prior ecosystem (bare rock, new volcanic island); secondary succession begins after disturbance removes the community but leaves soil intact (after fire, agriculture), and proceeds faster due to existing seed banks and nutrients', 'Both types of succession result in different climax communities', 'Secondary succession never reaches a stable climax community', 'B', 'Primary succession: lifeless substrate (bare rock, sand dune) → pioneer species (lichens, mosses) → soil formation → shrubs → forest. Secondary succession: disturbance removes vegetation but soil remains → rapid recolonization from seed banks, roots, soil organisms → recovery much faster than primary succession. Both proceed through seral stages toward a climax community characteristic of that region.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'How does lateral gene transfer complicate the construction of the universal tree of life?', 'Lateral gene transfer has no effect on phylogenetic trees', 'LGT moves genes between distantly related lineages, so different genes in the same organism can have different evolutionary histories — making a single bifurcating tree misleading; the actual evolutionary history may resemble a network rather than a tree', 'LGT only occurs between organisms of the same species', 'LGT always improves the accuracy of phylogenetic trees', 'B', 'Because LGT (especially in prokaryotes) transfers genes between very different lineages, a single "universal tree" based on any one gene may not reflect the whole-genome history. Core genes (rRNA, core metabolic genes less subject to LGT) may give a tree; but accessory genomes reflect a web of transfers. This has led to proposals that the early history of life is better represented as a network.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is stabilizing selection and give an example in humans?', 'Stabilizing selection drives the population mean toward an extreme phenotype', 'Stabilizing selection favors intermediate phenotypes and eliminates extremes, reducing phenotypic variance while maintaining the population mean; human birth weight is a classic example (very small and very large infants have higher mortality)', 'Stabilizing selection is the same as directional selection', 'Stabilizing selection increases genetic diversity', 'B', 'In stabilizing selection, fitness is highest for intermediate phenotypes and lower for both extremes. Human birth weight: before modern medicine, very low weight infants (higher risk of infection, respiratory failure) and very high weight infants (birth complications) had higher mortality; intermediate weight (~3–4 kg) was optimal.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'How do major histocompatibility complex (MHC) genes contribute to biodiversity and resistance to disease at the population level?', 'MHC genes have no function at the population level', 'MHC is the most polymorphic gene region in vertebrates; high MHC diversity in a population allows more individuals to present different pathogen peptides, providing broader collective resistance to the diverse pathogens a population may encounter', 'MHC diversity reduces individual disease resistance', 'MHC diversity is maintained only through mutation', 'B', 'Population-level MHC diversity (maintained by overdominant selection — heterozygotes have highest fitness — and frequency-dependent selection against common MHC types) ensures that no single pathogen peptide can escape presentation by ALL individuals in a population. This collective immunological breadth is a key defense against epidemic diseases.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the ecological significance of keystone predation?', 'Keystone predators reduce biodiversity by eliminating prey', 'Keystone predators maintain community diversity by preventing competitively dominant prey species from monopolizing resources; removing the keystone predator often causes a trophic cascade that collapses community structure', 'Keystone predators are the most abundant species in an ecosystem', 'Keystone predation increases ecosystem productivity', 'B', 'Paine''s classic seastar (Pisaster) experiments showed that removing the top predator allowed mussels (competitively dominant prey) to crowd out other species, dramatically reducing biodiversity. Keystone predation keeps dominant prey in check, maintaining the mosaic of species in the community. This is also illustrated by wolf reintroduction causing trophic cascades in Yellowstone.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is inclusive fitness, and how does it extend classical Darwinian fitness?', 'Inclusive fitness counts only an individual''s direct reproduction', 'Inclusive fitness includes both direct fitness (personal reproduction) and indirect fitness (copies of shared genes passed on through relatives aided by the individual''s behavior), allowing the evolution of altruism toward kin', 'Inclusive fitness is a measure of how many predators an organism avoids', 'Inclusive fitness applies only to social insects', 'B', 'Classical fitness measures only direct reproductive success. Inclusive fitness (Hamilton) adds indirect fitness — the propagation of shared alleles through reproductively successful relatives. Since parents and siblings share ~50% of alleles (r = 0.5), helping a sibling raise two extra offspring propagates as many shared alleles as having one extra offspring yourself — providing the mathematical basis for kin selection.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'What are the major adaptations that allowed plants to colonize terrestrial environments from aquatic ancestors?', 'Plants simply moved onto land without requiring any adaptations', 'Key adaptations include: cuticle (waxy coating reducing water loss), stomata (regulated gas exchange), vascular tissue (xylem/phloem for long-distance transport), roots (water/nutrient absorption and anchorage), lignin (structural support), and seeds/pollen (independent of water for reproduction)', 'The only adaptation required was the evolution of photosynthesis', 'Terrestrial plants evolved wings to disperse their gametes', 'B', 'Colonization of land by plants (~470 Mya from charophyte green algae ancestors) required solving: desiccation (cuticle, stomata), gravity (lignified cell walls, vascular tissue), reproduction without water (seeds, pollen for water-independent fertilization), and UV radiation (UV-absorbing compounds). These are reflected in the evolutionary sequence: bryophytes → vascular plants → seeds → angiosperms.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'diversity-of-life', 'How does the immune system of invertebrates differ from that of vertebrates?', 'Invertebrates have a fully developed adaptive immune system identical to vertebrates', 'Invertebrates rely entirely on innate immunity (phagocytes, antimicrobial peptides, pattern recognition receptors) and lack the adaptive immune system (T cells, B cells, immunological memory with antigen-specific receptors) found in vertebrates', 'Invertebrates use antibodies as their primary defense', 'Invertebrate immune responses are slower than those of vertebrates', 'B', 'Invertebrates (insects, worms, molluscs) rely on innate immunity: phagocytic hemocytes, antimicrobial peptides (defensins, cecropins), Toll/Toll-like receptor pathways, melanization (pro-phenoloxidase cascade in arthropods), and RNAi-based antiviral defense. They lack the RAG-mediated V(D)J recombination and somatic hypermutation that generate adaptive immune diversity in vertebrates.'),

-- hard diversity-of-life
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'Explain the Asgard hypothesis for the origin of eukaryotes and what genomic evidence supports it.', 'Eukaryotes evolved from ancient bacteria by acquiring a nucleus', 'Metagenomics revealed the Asgard archaea (including Lokiarchaeota, Thorarchaeota) as the closest prokaryotic relatives of eukaryotes; they encode eukaryotic-signature proteins (ESPs) such as actin, ESCRT-III, and GTPases related to vesicle trafficking — suggesting the host cell of the proto-eukaryotic merger was an archaeon that contributed eukaryotic information-processing genes, with an alphaproteobacterium endosymbiont becoming the mitochondrion', 'Eukaryotes evolved from gram-positive bacteria based on cell wall structure', 'The Asgard hypothesis proposes that all eukaryotes descended from a single fungal ancestor', 'B', 'Asgard archaea (discovered by metagenomic sequencing of deep-sea sediments) possess homologs of eukaryotic proteins: Lokiarchaeota encode actin and actin-binding proteins, GTPases, ESCRT-III subunits, and ubiquitin-like modifiers — all involved in eukaryotic membrane dynamics. Phylogenomics places Asgard archaea as the sister group to eukaryotes. The two-domain hypothesis proposes that eukaryotes evolved FROM within Archaea (specifically Asgard), with a subsequent mitochondrial endosymbiosis.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is sexual selection, and explain how both intrasexual and intersexual selection drive the evolution of secondary sexual characteristics?', 'Sexual selection is simply natural selection applied to reproduction', 'Sexual selection arises from competition for mates: intrasexual selection (same-sex competition, usually males) favors traits useful in fighting rivals (antlers, larger body size); intersexual selection (mate choice, usually female choice) favors traits signaling genetic quality (elaborate plumage, songs) even if costly — explaining the evolution of apparently maladaptive extravagant traits', 'Sexual selection always acts identically to natural selection and produces the same outcomes', 'Only intersexual selection (mate choice) is a form of sexual selection', 'B', 'Darwin''s sexual selection: intrasexual (male-male competition) drives weapons (antlers, large body, fighting ability); intersexual (female choice) drives ornaments (peacock tail, bird-of-paradise displays, frog calls). Fisher''s runaway selection and Zahavian honest-signal handicap models explain why exaggerated costly traits evolve: they signal genetic quality (parasite resistance, vigorous health) that is heritable and benefits offspring.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'How does the neutral theory of molecular evolution by Motoo Kimura challenge the adaptationist paradigm, and what evidence supports it?', 'Neutral theory proposes that all mutations are beneficial', 'Neutral theory proposes that most molecular variation (especially at the DNA level) is selectively neutral, fixed by genetic drift rather than natural selection; evidence: synonymous substitution rates are much higher than nonsynonymous rates, pseudogene divergence equals synonymous rates, and the nearly constant rate of molecular evolution across lineages (molecular clock)', 'Neutral theory and the adaptationist program make identical predictions about molecular diversity', 'Neutral theory has been completely disproven by genomic data', 'B', 'Kimura (1968) proposed that most amino acid and nucleotide substitutions in evolution are neutral (fitness effect ≈ 0) and fixed by drift. Evidence: (1) dN/dS (nonsynonymous/synonymous substitution ratio) < 1 for most genes (purifying selection removes deleterious changes; synonymous positions near-neutral); (2) pseudogenes (no function, all mutations neutral) diverge at the same rate as synonymous sites; (3) the approximately linear molecular clock.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'Describe the evolutionary origin of multicellularity, including what transition steps are required and evidence from model organisms.', 'Multicellularity evolved only once in animals from a unicellular ancestor', 'Multicellularity evolved independently at least 25 times; key transitions require cells remaining together after division, cell differentiation, cooperation over competition (requiring mechanisms to suppress cheating), and intercellular communication; Volvox and Choanoflagellates model early stages', 'Multicellularity requires horizontal gene transfer from bacteria', 'All multicellular organisms evolved from the same common unicellular ancestor', 'B', 'Multicellularity evolved independently in animals, plants, fungi, red/brown/green algae, myxobacteria, and others — at least 25 times. Required steps: (1) cellular adhesion (cadherin-like and fibronectin-like proteins in choanoflagellates, basal to animals); (2) division of labor (differentiation); (3) cell signaling; (4) policing mechanisms against "cheater" cells that could outcompete cooperative cells. The Volvocales (from unicellular Chlamydomonas to colonial Gonium to differentiated Volvox) serve as a model for progressive multicellularity.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the evolutionary and ecological significance of the microbiome, and how does disruption of the microbiome (dysbiosis) affect host fitness?', 'The microbiome is an irrelevant collection of parasites that must be eliminated for health', 'The human gut microbiome (~38 trillion bacteria) provides metabolic capabilities the host genome lacks (fiber digestion, vitamin synthesis), shapes immune system development, modulates the gut-brain axis, and competitively excludes pathogens; dysbiosis is associated with IBD, obesity, allergies, anxiety, and increased pathogen susceptibility', 'The microbiome affects only digestive function and no other body systems', 'Dysbiosis always increases host fitness by providing more diverse metabolic options', 'B', 'The gut microbiome contributes to host fitness through: (1) metabolic expansion — SCFAs from fiber fermentation feed colonocytes; vitamin B12, K2 synthesis; (2) immune maturation — germ-free mice have underdeveloped immune systems; colonization with normal flora (especially early-life Bacteroidetes/Firmicutes) is required for regulatory T cell development; (3) colonization resistance against pathogens; (4) gut-brain axis via vagal signals, tryptophan metabolism, and SCFA effects on brain function.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'How does the evolution of the eye illustrate both the power and constraints of natural selection, using molecular evidence?', 'Each eye type in different animals evolved from a completely different gene', 'Despite multiple independent origins of complex eyes (compound in arthropods, camera in cephalopods and vertebrates), the same master regulatory gene Pax6 controls eye development across taxa — illustrating that evolution reuses deeply conserved developmental toolkits even in convergent structures, but the specific optical solutions (lens, mirror, compound) reflect different historical paths and constraints', 'Eyes evolved only once, in vertebrates, and all animal eyes are homologous', 'Natural selection cannot act on complex structures like eyes', 'B', 'The eye is a textbook case of both convergence and deep homology. Pax6 is required for eye development in insects, vertebrates, squid, and flatworms — its deep conservation suggests an ancient common regulatory role. Yet the optical designs (vertebrate camera eye, insect compound eye, scallop mirror eye, pinhole nautilus eye) are non-homologous (different developmental origins, genes for lens proteins). Evolution has converged on "useful light-detecting organ" using the same master switch but different molecular machinery.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the evolutionary significance of the Hox gene cluster, and what evidence suggests it has been crucial for animal body plan diversification?', 'Hox genes specify only leg development in arthropods', 'Hox genes are a conserved cluster of transcription factors that specify anterior-posterior body axis identity in all bilaterian animals; variations in Hox gene number, expression patterns, and target genes explain much of the diversity in body plans; their collinear organization is conserved from flies to humans', 'Hox genes evolved independently in arthropods and vertebrates without any common ancestor', 'Hox gene mutations always cause lethality and cannot drive evolution', 'B', 'Hox genes (homeodomain TFs in a cluster) specify positional identity along the A-P axis. Key evidence for their body plan role: (1) temporal and spatial collinearity (Hox1 expressed anteriorly, Hox13 posteriorly, in order along chromosome); (2) homeotic mutations change segment identity (Antennapedia in Drosophila: legs on head); (3) Hox gene expression differences explain vertebral formula variation in snakes vs. other mammals; (4) Hox cluster expansion from 1 (ancestral) to 4 clusters (vertebrates) correlates with increased morphological complexity.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'Describe how mass extinctions shape evolutionary history, using the Cretaceous-Paleogene (K-Pg) extinction as a case study.', 'Mass extinctions reduce biodiversity permanently with no subsequent radiation', 'The K-Pg event (~66 Ma, bolide impact + Deccan volcanism) caused >75% species loss including non-avian dinosaurs; the resulting ecological vacuums were filled by rapid adaptive radiations, particularly of placental mammals, which diversified into ecological roles previously occupied by dinosaurs — demonstrating that mass extinctions restructure evolutionary opportunity', 'The K-Pg extinction was caused entirely by a gradual ice age over millions of years', 'Mammals were not affected by the K-Pg extinction', 'B', 'K-Pg evidence: Chicxulub crater, worldwide iridium anomaly (Alvarez), global wildfires, impact winter (dust/sulfate aerosols blocking sunlight → photosynthesis collapse), acid rain. Non-avian dinosaurs (except avian lineage) went extinct, along with ~75% of species. Aftermath: placental mammals (which survived as small, nocturnal insectivores) rapidly diversified in the Paleocene/Eocene into carnivores, herbivores, grazers, arboreal species, whales — the greatest mammalian adaptive radiation.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is frequency-dependent selection, and explain how it maintains polymorphism in predator-prey systems?', 'Frequency-dependent selection always eliminates the rarer morph from a population', 'In negative frequency-dependent selection, rare morphs have higher fitness than common morphs (e.g., rare prey color forms are less recognized by predators with search image), maintaining multiple morphs in the population in a stable equilibrium — a powerful mechanism for maintaining genetic diversity', 'Frequency-dependent selection requires sexual reproduction', 'Only positive frequency-dependent selection maintains polymorphism', 'B', 'Negative frequency-dependent selection: fitness of a morph is inversely related to its frequency. Classic example: shell color polymorphism in Cepaea snails — predatory birds form search images for the most common morph, making rare morphs harder to find and therefore more fit. This creates a balancing selection that maintains multiple color morphs at stable frequencies. Also explains self-incompatibility alleles in plants and MHC diversity.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'How do transposable elements (TEs) contribute to genome evolution and biodiversity?', 'Transposable elements are always harmful parasitic sequences that are entirely suppressed', 'TEs (jumping genes) can disrupt coding sequences, alter gene regulation by inserting near promoters or enhancers, shuffle exons, create new regulatory sequences (transposable element domestication), and generate chromosomal rearrangements — they have been exapted for host functions including immune genes (RAG1/2 from Transib transposons) and are major contributors to genome size variation', 'Transposable elements only affect gene expression in somatic cells', 'TEs cannot be passed to offspring because they are cleared from germ cells', 'B', 'TEs comprise >45% of the human genome and >80% of some plant genomes. Their contributions: (1) exon shuffling via TE-mediated recombination; (2) new regulatory elements (SINE-derived enhancers, endogenous retroviral LTRs repurposed as promoters — e.g., ERV-derived syncytins for placenta formation); (3) RAG1/2 recombinase (V(D)J immunity) derived from ancient Transib transposases; (4) heterochromatin formation at pericentromeres; (5) LINE-1 retrotransposition creates somatic mosaicism in the brain.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is ecological stoichiometry, and how does the ratio of carbon to nitrogen to phosphorus constrain trophic efficiency?', 'Stoichiometry refers only to the chemical reactions in ecosystems', 'Ecological stoichiometry examines the balance of chemical elements in organisms and their interactions; animals have relatively fixed elemental ratios (high P for rRNA in fast-growing animals), while plants and prey may have different C:N:P ratios — imbalanced ratios between prey and predator force the consumer to excrete excess elements, limiting growth efficiency', 'All organisms have identical C:N:P ratios and stoichiometry does not constrain food webs', 'Phosphorus stoichiometry only affects primary producers', 'B', 'Ecological stoichiometry (Sterner & Elser): organisms maintain homeostatic elemental composition. Fast-growing animals need high P for ribosomal RNA; if prey is P-poor (high C:P), predators must consume more food and excrete excess C, reducing growth efficiency. The growth rate hypothesis links fast growth to high P demand, linking organismal physiology to ecosystem nutrient cycling and explaining why P limitation affects multiple trophic levels.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'How has the evolution of flight independently in birds, bats, and pterosaurs each required different morphological solutions, illustrating the role of historical constraints in evolution?', 'All flying vertebrates have identical wing structures derived from the same ancestral wings', 'Flight evolved three times in vertebrates with different ancestral forelimb modifications: birds (arm bones fused, feathers from modified scales), bats (greatly elongated digits supporting a patagial membrane), and pterosaurs (a single elongated fourth digit supporting the wing membrane) — each solution reflects the different ancestral hand morphology available and represents convergence on flight with divergent structural details', 'Convergent evolution requires identical solutions; therefore all wings must be homologous', 'Pterosaurs did not actually fly — they only glided', 'B', 'Flight convergence illustrates how selection for the same function (powered flight) achieves it through different structural means, constrained by historical/phylogenetic legacy. Birds: forelimb bones (carpals fused to metacarpal = carpometacarpus) + feathers from epidermal scales provide lift. Bats: greatly elongated digits 2–5 support a patagio of skin. Pterosaurs: a single hypertrophied 4th digit supports the wing membrane. Each uses available "raw material" (ancestral tetrapod forelimb) reorganized by natural selection for flight.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'Describe the molecular basis of plant recognition of pathogens and the resulting defense responses (PTI and ETI).', 'Plants use antibodies to recognize and destroy pathogens', 'Plants recognize PAMPs via pattern recognition receptors (PRRs, e.g., FLS2 for bacterial flagellin) → PAMP-triggered immunity (PTI); pathogens inject effectors to suppress PTI; plants evolved intracellular NLR receptors that recognize effectors → effector-triggered immunity (ETI), a stronger HR response involving hypersensitive cell death — an evolutionary arms race', 'Plants have no immune system and rely solely on physical barriers', 'ETI occurs before PTI and is always the first line of plant defense', 'B', 'Plant immunity (zigzag model): (1) PRRs (LRR-RLKs like FLS2, EFR) at cell surface detect PAMPs (flagellin, EF-Tu) → PTI (MAPK cascades, callose deposition, antimicrobial compound synthesis); (2) pathogen effectors (delivered by T3SS in bacteria) suppress PTI; (3) intracellular NLR proteins (TIR-NBS-LRR or CC-NBS-LRR) recognize effectors (directly or via guarded/decoy proteins) → ETI; (4) ETI triggers hypersensitive response (HR) — local programmed cell death limiting pathogen spread, and systemic acquired resistance (SAR) via salicylic acid signaling.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the red queen hypothesis, and how does it explain the evolutionary maintenance of sexual reproduction despite its two-fold cost?', 'The red queen hypothesis explains why predators evolve faster than prey', 'The red queen hypothesis proposes that organisms must continually evolve to maintain fitness relative to their coevolving parasites and pathogens; sex generates novel genotype combinations that can outpace pathogen adaptation to host genotypes — the short-term "cost" of sex (only ~50% of offspring reproduce) is offset by the long-term benefit of diverse offspring resistant to parasites', 'The red queen hypothesis applies only to asexual organisms', 'The two-fold cost of sex is not a real problem in evolutionary biology', 'B', 'Two-fold cost of sex: asexual females produce 2× as many offspring per individual since all offspring reproduce, while sexual species "waste" half their reproductive output on males. Red Queen resolution: parasites rapidly evolve to exploit the most common host genotype. Sexual reproduction creates genotypically diverse offspring; rare genotypes are harder for co-evolving parasites to infect. Evidence: New Zealand snail (Potamopyrgus) populations shift to sexual reproduction where trematode parasitism is highest.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'Explain the molecular basis of nitrogen fixation and why this process is so energetically costly.', 'Nitrogen fixation is performed by plants directly using photosynthetic energy', 'Biological nitrogen fixation is catalyzed by nitrogenase (an Fe-Mo protein complex) that reduces N₂ to NH₃ using 16 ATP and 8 electrons per N₂ molecule; nitrogenase is irreversibly inactivated by O₂, requiring special adaptations (heterocysts in cyanobacteria, nodule O₂ management in legumes) — the triple bond of N₂ requires enormous activation energy to break', 'Nitrogen fixation is an aerobic process requiring high O₂ concentrations', 'The energy cost of nitrogen fixation is similar to other metabolic processes', 'B', 'Nitrogenase complex: the Fe protein (dinitrogenase reductase) uses 2 ATP per electron delivered to the MoFe protein (dinitrogenase), which contains the FeMo-cofactor (FeMoco) active site where N₂ binds. Overall: N₂ + 8H⁺ + 8e⁻ + 16ATP → 2NH₃ + H₂ + 16ADP + 16Pi. O₂ irreversibly destroys nitrogenase: cyanobacteria use thick-walled heterocysts (losing PSII, maintaining high O₂ consumption); legume root nodules have leghemoglobin (binding O₂ to keep free O₂ concentration low while allowing O₂ for bacteroid respiration).'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is developmental plasticity, and how does it relate to the concept of reaction norms in evolutionary biology?', 'Developmental plasticity means that all traits are fully determined by genetics at birth', 'Developmental plasticity is the capacity of one genotype to produce different phenotypes in different environments; a reaction norm describes the range of phenotypes a single genotype produces across environmental conditions — wide reaction norms allow organisms to match phenotype to environment, and plasticity itself is heritable and subject to selection', 'Reaction norms describe only morphological traits, not behavioral or physiological ones', 'Developmental plasticity reduces fitness by producing non-optimal phenotypes', 'B', 'Developmental plasticity enables a single genotype to produce multiple phenotypes (polyphenism) in response to environmental cues: Daphnia develop helmets in predator-conditioned water; temperature-dependent sex determination in reptiles; phenotypic accommodation. The reaction norm (phenotype vs. environment plot for one genotype) can be steep (high plasticity) or flat (low plasticity). The shape of the reaction norm is itself a heritable character under selection — West-Eberhard''s view that plasticity can facilitate genetic accommodation of adaptive phenotypes.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'How does the evolution of antibiotic resistance in bacteria illustrate all five components of evolution simultaneously?', 'Only natural selection is involved in antibiotic resistance evolution', 'In bacterial populations: (1) mutation provides resistance alleles; (2) gene flow spreads resistance via conjugation/transformation (HGT); (3) genetic drift can fix resistance in small bottlenecked populations; (4) natural selection eliminates susceptible bacteria when antibiotics are present; (5) these changes alter allele frequencies (evolution); together they rapidly produce resistant populations in clinical settings', 'Antibiotic resistance evolves through directed mutation, not random processes', 'Genetic drift is irrelevant to antibiotic resistance because bacterial populations are very large', 'B', 'All evolutionary mechanisms act simultaneously on bacterial antibiotic resistance: Mutation — random point mutations in drug targets (rpoB for rifampicin resistance) or drug-modifying enzyme genes arise continuously; HGT (gene flow) — R plasmids move resistance genes between strains and species via conjugation; Genetic drift — hospital-associated bottlenecks and founder effects can fix resistance; Natural selection — the powerful directional selection of antibiotic treatment eliminates susceptible bacteria. Together these mechanisms produce MDR (multidrug-resistant) bacteria rapidly.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'Explain how the evolution of C4 photosynthesis represents an adaptive response to falling atmospheric CO₂ and rising temperatures, and describe the phylogenetic evidence for convergent evolution of C4.', 'C4 photosynthesis evolved once in a single ancestor of all C4 plants', 'C4 photosynthesis evolved independently >60 times in angiosperms (representing the most extreme case of convergent evolution in plants) as CO₂ declined and temperatures rose ~35–25 Mya; it reduces photorespiration via CO₂ concentrating mechanisms involving PEP carboxylase in mesophyll and RuBisCO in bundle sheath cells, particularly advantageous in hot, open, low-CO₂ environments', 'C4 photosynthesis is only beneficial in cold, aquatic environments', 'All grasses are C4; no other plant families have C4 species', 'B', 'Declining Cenozoic CO₂ (from ~1500 ppm pre-Cretaceous to <350 ppm today) increased RuBisCO oxygenase activity (photorespiration), reducing C3 plant efficiency. C4 evolved ≥61 independent times across 19 angiosperm families (PACMAD clade grasses, Caryophyllales, etc.) — evidenced by molecular phylogenetics placing C4 species in multiple non-monophyletic clades. The C4 biochemical pump (PEPC + decarboxylase + Kranz anatomy) essentially re-evolved the same solution independently ≥60 times from C3 ancestors.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'What is the major transition theory (Maynard Smith and Szathmáry), and how does it organize the history of life?', 'Major transitions theory describes only the evolution of multicellularity', 'Major transitions are moments in evolution where the nature of information storage/transmission changed fundamentally, including: origin of replicating molecules, RNA world to DNA+protein, origin of the cell (chromosome), prokaryote to eukaryote cell (endosymbiosis), asexual to sexual reproduction, single-celled to multicellular organisms, and eusociality — each transition involved new levels of individuality and division of labor', 'Major transitions theory only applies to the evolution of animals', 'Major transitions are defined entirely by mass extinction events', 'B', 'Maynard Smith & Szathmáry identified ~8 major transitions characterized by: (1) lower-level units forming higher-level units; (2) information previously housed in lower levels now encoded at higher level; (3) division of labor making individual components non-viable alone. Transitions: replicating molecules → chromosomes → cells → eukaryotic cell → sexual populations → multicellular organisms → eusocial colonies → language-based human societies. Each transition restructured how Darwinian evolution operates.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'diversity-of-life', 'How do the principles of island biogeography (MacArthur and Wilson) explain patterns of species richness on islands, and what conservation implications does the theory have?', 'Island biogeography predicts that large, distant islands have the most species', 'Island species richness reaches an equilibrium determined by immigration rate (decreasing with distance from mainland) and extinction rate (decreasing with island area); larger islands have lower extinction rates (more resources, habitat diversity); closer islands have higher immigration rates — this dynamic equilibrium model predicts species turnover without total richness change and informs habitat fragment conservation', 'The theory predicts that species richness is determined only by island age', 'Conservation reserves should be designed as many small fragments to maximize total species number', 'B', 'MacArthur-Wilson model: immigration rate from mainland decreases with island distance (fewer dispersers arrive); extinction rate decreases with island area (larger islands support larger populations less prone to stochastic extinction). Equilibrium species number S̃ = immigration rate / extinction rate × time. Conservation implications (SLOSS debate): the model suggests that larger reserves have lower extinction rates and are better than multiple small fragments of the same total area; habitat corridors function as bridges reducing isolation and extinction rates.');
